So there has never been a discussion over the last three

736
00:40:00.430 --> 00:40:04.150
years about not meeting obligations, about not improving environmental

737
00:40:04.210 --> 00:40:07.690
outcomes, about not finding ways to achieve more,

738
00:40:08.390 --> 00:40:12.170
and to produce more. The two have to go hand in hand together.

739
00:40:12.210 --> 00:40:13.550
And the reason for that is that

740
00:40:14.430 --> 00:40:17.750
the reputation that we have helps products be chosen

741
00:40:17.790 --> 00:40:21.679
overseas over those from other like-minded similar countries

742
00:40:21.710 --> 00:40:25.350
we might be compared to. We're focused, over the last three years,

743
00:40:25.430 --> 00:40:29.239
on simplifying these rules, but simplifying means easier

744
00:40:29.310 --> 00:40:33.070
to achieve what is needed rather than just adding

745
00:40:33.450 --> 00:40:37.190
cost. And that work should always continue as

746
00:40:37.250 --> 00:40:41.230
farmers continue to look for ways to improve what they do to be

747
00:40:41.239 --> 00:40:45.010
more effective, to be more efficient, to reduce costs, to be more

748
00:40:45.090 --> 00:40:48.900
careful about what they spend, to produce more whilst caring about the

749
00:40:48.930 --> 00:40:50.910
environment and selling more overseas.

750
00:40:50.990 --> 00:40:54.519
The more we get to sell overseas, the greater the return, the better off every New

751
00:40:54.570 --> 00:40:55.050
Zealander is.

752
00:40:57.450 --> 00:40:57.650
Yeah.

753
00:40:58.670 --> 00:41:00.010
Minister, predictions

754
00:41:00.910 --> 00:41:03.250
for the future for primary industries?

755
00:41:04.390 --> 00:41:08.330
Look, I'm extremely optimistic. I think there has not been for a

756
00:41:08.370 --> 00:41:11.990
long time, a better time to be a farmer or a grower in New Zealand or anywhere in

757
00:41:12.030 --> 00:41:12.430
the world.

758
00:41:13.470 --> 00:41:14.270
And the face of

759
00:41:15.090 --> 00:41:18.610
significant headwinds from tariff rates and change in the

760
00:41:18.670 --> 00:41:22.510
US to input costs that have gone up because of the war in the Middle East to

761
00:41:22.610 --> 00:41:26.520
other types of uncertainty and so on, our farmers have year on year,

762
00:41:27.190 --> 00:41:30.740
doing well, doing extremely well for New Zealand, as others

763
00:41:30.830 --> 00:41:34.470
are. The demand for protein continues to increase.

764
00:41:34.830 --> 00:41:38.450
Part of the reason you are seeing good dairy returns, I am

765
00:41:38.510 --> 00:41:42.350
told, and you'll see newspaper articles around this if you look around the world,

766
00:41:42.860 --> 00:41:46.790
is the advent of the desire for people to be healthier

767
00:41:46.890 --> 00:41:50.870
as they lose weight. And when you get Starbucks in America buying

768
00:41:50.890 --> 00:41:54.650
dairy protein to add to their coffee so it has

769
00:41:54.710 --> 00:41:58.230
higher protein in it, it tells me that our farmers are in a pretty good place.

770
00:41:58.530 --> 00:42:00.430
But it's not only dairy. You've seen

771
00:42:01.610 --> 00:42:04.130
meat prices increase as demand has.

772
00:42:04.270 --> 00:42:06.870
This is not just about commodity anymore.

773
00:42:07.070 --> 00:42:10.550
In China, I might have mentioned when I was here last year before you,

774
00:42:11.090 --> 00:42:14.850
one of the meat companies there has launched a burger that is

775
00:42:14.890 --> 00:42:18.850
ready to eat, ready to heat, ready to cook, and the value is added in

776
00:42:18.870 --> 00:42:22.100
New Zealand. And the return they're getting for that, along with many other

777
00:42:22.130 --> 00:42:23.690
products with the value added here,

778
00:42:24.510 --> 00:42:28.350
with that New Zealand grass-fed standard put on it that the government has

779
00:42:28.410 --> 00:42:32.020
developed by sector and is promoting, is exceptional.

780
00:42:32.080 --> 00:42:35.900
And so there's a lot of interest. The final that I would touch on is it's

781
00:42:35.950 --> 00:42:39.830
very broad for the kiwi fruit that is going great returns

782
00:42:39.890 --> 00:42:43.500
for New Zealand, and it's called kiwi fruit, not Chilean fruit or

783
00:42:43.550 --> 00:42:46.450
Australian fruit or European fruit. It's Chilean fruit.

784
00:42:46.750 --> 00:42:48.290
But I want to make you think about the wool industry.

785
00:42:48.330 --> 00:42:52.270
When we came to government three years ago, sheep farmers were hardly making money

786
00:42:52.350 --> 00:42:56.330
on their lamb, and they were losing money in wool, and there were suggestions that

787
00:42:56.370 --> 00:42:59.930
the wool industry would be over. Actually now, they're making-

788
00:43:00.682 --> 00:43:03.762
Money again. They're getting a greater return than their cost.

789
00:43:04.222 --> 00:43:07.622
That's a number of things. The price has gone up.

790
00:43:08.042 --> 00:43:11.302
There are greater utilizations of wool

791
00:43:11.862 --> 00:43:15.682
being used, and last week we announced $8 million, I think it was, for the

792
00:43:15.822 --> 00:43:19.522
Primary Sector Growth Fund to help the next stage to develop other uses

793
00:43:19.642 --> 00:43:23.442
of the wool itself, from pigments to dyes, to all sorts of

794
00:43:23.462 --> 00:43:27.242
things like this, which is a greater value than the wool itself, to

795
00:43:27.882 --> 00:43:31.582
people seeking out New Zealand wool because it's strong to add to

796
00:43:31.602 --> 00:43:33.241
garments and carpets around the world.

797
00:43:33.272 --> 00:43:36.862
The India free trade agreement goes to a zero tariff rate for wool on day one.

798
00:43:37.562 --> 00:43:41.442
When I was there, the day before the signing, I met in a meeting a man who has

799
00:43:41.462 --> 00:43:45.422
a carpet mill. There's a chance his carpet mill produces more carpet

800
00:43:45.442 --> 00:43:47.162
than the whole of New Zealand does.

801
00:43:47.582 --> 00:43:48.802
He sells in India and

802
00:43:50.262 --> 00:43:54.102
the countries around India. He uses

803
00:43:54.112 --> 00:43:56.982
some New Zealand wool because of the strong nature to blend with theirs.

804
00:43:57.022 --> 00:44:00.751
When I met with him, he said, "With the tariff rate coming to zero, I am only going

805
00:44:00.902 --> 00:44:04.861
to use New Zealand wool because of its quality." And if he is producing carpets and

806
00:44:04.942 --> 00:44:08.212
rugs that are of a premium value,

807
00:44:08.862 --> 00:44:12.212
then whilst it will be a commercial negotiation as to what you pay for the wool

808
00:44:12.222 --> 00:44:15.682
from New Zealand, if he doesn't have the wool, he can't make the carpet to sell.

809
00:44:15.722 --> 00:44:19.662
So I think across the board, farmers are right to be

810
00:44:19.682 --> 00:44:23.362
feeling good. They are right to be smiling at field days, and I thank them for

811
00:44:23.382 --> 00:44:26.722
their hard work. We've all got to just work hard to keep backing them, keep rules

812
00:44:26.762 --> 00:44:29.752
simple, so they can meet their obligations to keep selling the highest quality,

813
00:44:29.802 --> 00:44:30.782
safest product in the world.

814
00:44:31.422 --> 00:44:31.782
Thank you.

815
00:44:33.222 --> 00:44:37.152
I've got a quick sup. So do you think the focus on reducing red tape

816
00:44:37.202 --> 00:44:41.062
and increasing productivity, it's good for farmers and it's

817
00:44:41.102 --> 00:44:41.542
good for

818
00:44:42.702 --> 00:44:46.442
growth, but it also has a flow on effect for New Zealand consumers?

819
00:44:46.662 --> 00:44:49.222
If you're reducing the cost of production, it's good for consumers too.

820
00:44:49.302 --> 00:44:49.522
Yeah.

821
00:44:50.362 --> 00:44:54.322
So certainly where you can get cost out of a system, as you've heard us say around

822
00:44:54.542 --> 00:44:58.422
the economies we're going to make in the primary MPI budget,

823
00:44:58.982 --> 00:45:00.802
finding efficiencies is not a bad thing.

824
00:45:01.382 --> 00:45:01.492
Mm-hmm.

825
00:45:01.582 --> 00:45:05.502
Organizations, companies, businesses that keep doing what they've always

826
00:45:05.542 --> 00:45:07.242
done and adding cost, in the end,

827
00:45:08.102 --> 00:45:11.902
go out of business. And government, if you keep doing that, you have to put

828
00:45:11.962 --> 00:45:14.702
taxes up, where a government that doesn't want to increase taxes, we want to be

829
00:45:14.742 --> 00:45:16.841
very careful with taxpayer resource.

830
00:45:17.542 --> 00:45:21.342
So the answer is yes. It is very hard for a government

831
00:45:21.722 --> 00:45:23.882
to do something about what farmers earn.

832
00:45:23.962 --> 00:45:27.522
We can do free trade agreements and give them better access, but actually,

833
00:45:27.622 --> 00:45:29.382
prices often are set internationally.

834
00:45:29.422 --> 00:45:33.342
We can help them add value and to promote to be

835
00:45:33.382 --> 00:45:36.482
chosen first. That grass-fed standard is a very good example of that.

836
00:45:36.522 --> 00:45:39.802
But ultimately, international markets often will set a price.

837
00:45:40.112 --> 00:45:40.282
Sure.

838
00:45:40.292 --> 00:45:44.142
We have an absolute obligation to focus on the costs that are created and put upon

839
00:45:44.322 --> 00:45:46.182
businesses, and in this case, farmers.

840
00:45:46.202 --> 00:45:49.982
And so we've been looking to find efficiencies and better ways to achieve what we

841
00:45:50.022 --> 00:45:50.362
need to.

842
00:45:51.182 --> 00:45:54.922
But it's not just about the cost to consumers and whether that's being

843
00:45:55.002 --> 00:45:58.582
passed on or not. You get better environment and climate outcomes

844
00:45:58.922 --> 00:46:01.362
when you work with people and you find solutions.

845
00:46:02.182 --> 00:46:06.062
I want to use the example, just because it is one that was raised with

846
00:46:06.142 --> 00:46:10.122
me in a meeting in my electorate yesterday, of the Ute Tax.

847
00:46:10.482 --> 00:46:14.102
There is a desire, many more people are purchasing electric

848
00:46:14.182 --> 00:46:18.102
vehicles at the moment. But taxes change behavior, and if you want

849
00:46:18.122 --> 00:46:21.082
somebody to alter their behavior with a tax, they have to have an alternative to be

850
00:46:21.142 --> 00:46:24.542
able to do it. In the case of Ute Tax, where there wasn't an electric

851
00:46:24.782 --> 00:46:28.482
vehicle that could replace it, it just became a tax that either is

852
00:46:28.542 --> 00:46:31.062
a cost to the business or it gets passed on.

853
00:46:31.362 --> 00:46:35.282
There are better ways to find efficiencies when it comes to the utilization of

854
00:46:35.742 --> 00:46:39.582
fuel and other things and so on. Some of the projects that farmers are doing

855
00:46:39.602 --> 00:46:43.482
themselves of how can I use my tractor less to do the same amount

856
00:46:43.522 --> 00:46:47.242
of work to reduce a cost? And that's just something the government should always

857
00:46:47.302 --> 00:46:49.382
focus on and continue to work with, so.

858
00:46:50.222 --> 00:46:51.882
Thank you. I've got a question from Jo.

859
00:46:52.042 --> 00:46:52.662
Thank you.

860
00:46:53.842 --> 00:46:55.522
I just want to come back to the

861
00:46:57.782 --> 00:47:01.402
savings that the ministry is looking to find.

862
00:47:02.202 --> 00:47:03.222
And I note that

863
00:47:04.122 --> 00:47:07.942
some may be found by ending or scaling back

864
00:47:08.082 --> 00:47:09.842
low-value programs.

865
00:47:11.762 --> 00:47:12.642
I just want to know, what

866
00:47:13.642 --> 00:47:17.342
criteria or evidence are you going to be looking at or using to determine what has

867
00:47:17.381 --> 00:47:21.162
been a low-value program that you will no longer continue to?

868
00:47:21.262 --> 00:47:25.082
Well, I'll let Ray answer that in detail, but my expectation is

869
00:47:25.102 --> 00:47:27.942
projects that are taking too long and are not achieving what they need to, or the

870
00:47:28.002 --> 00:47:31.422
money can be better utilized elsewhere

871
00:47:31.482 --> 00:47:35.242
within the system to drive a better outcome more quickly,

872
00:47:35.602 --> 00:47:38.542
is an example of that. So if I come back to the Primary Sector Growth Fund,

873
00:47:40.382 --> 00:47:44.322
it's had a number of iterations. It started a long time ago when we

874
00:47:44.342 --> 00:47:48.142
were last in government. The name was changed with a change of government

875
00:47:48.182 --> 00:47:49.822
under Labor, and I've had a look at it.

876
00:47:49.862 --> 00:47:53.602
And so what we've been able to do there is say all the projects are worthy,

877
00:47:54.082 --> 00:47:57.602
but actually, some of them, the government feels like the taxpayer has a

878
00:47:57.682 --> 00:48:01.562
greater share than they might. And I'm a firm believer

879
00:48:01.602 --> 00:48:05.382
in the case of these projects is those that are asking us to support them should

880
00:48:05.422 --> 00:48:08.822
have more skin in the game rather than merely socializing risk.

881
00:48:09.202 --> 00:48:12.882
There is sometimes a need for governments to do things that others would argue

882
00:48:12.922 --> 00:48:16.802
might not, to try and get that next idea that's going to help the sector to

883
00:48:16.882 --> 00:48:20.662
solve the facial eczema problem, as an example.

884
00:48:21.062 --> 00:48:24.682
But what we did within that was, rather than reducing the amount we

885
00:48:24.782 --> 00:48:27.742
spent or canning it,

886
00:48:28.522 --> 00:48:31.812
refocused it for the outcome, so that to the short to medium term,

887
00:48:32.422 --> 00:48:36.212
there is more likely to be a greater return at the farm

888
00:48:36.302 --> 00:48:40.152
gate for the farmer. But also then saying, but other projects that take longer

889
00:48:40.302 --> 00:48:43.962
that actually could have a greater positive effect upon agriculture as a

890
00:48:44.042 --> 00:48:44.382
whole,

891
00:48:45.222 --> 00:48:48.922
then they could too be supported. But maybe there's some

892
00:48:48.942 --> 00:48:49.682
specific detail.

893
00:48:50.002 --> 00:48:50.642
Yeah, no. I think-

894
00:48:51.910 --> 00:48:54.310
We spent a lot of money. It's a large budget.

895
00:48:54.670 --> 00:48:57.920
We buy a lot of services, and we buy a lot of services from a lot of people,

896
00:48:58.590 --> 00:49:02.450
and we will continue to seek to make changes to who

897
00:49:02.510 --> 00:49:04.260
we buy from so we get the best value.

898
00:49:05.750 --> 00:49:09.570
And we've made some adjustments over time, where I think we've brought new

899
00:49:09.610 --> 00:49:12.450
service providers on that have given us better value for money than others.

900
00:49:12.510 --> 00:49:16.250
You'd expect us to do that. And so there's always gains that you can make

901
00:49:17.310 --> 00:49:19.309
in terms of the value you're getting for your money.

902
00:49:20.690 --> 00:49:23.630
And when I think in an overall sense,

903
00:49:23.690 --> 00:49:26.950
there's those services that are very

904
00:49:26.970 --> 00:49:30.930
directly delivering something every day to frontline consumers,

905
00:49:31.290 --> 00:49:34.890
and then there's a whole range of more discretionary elements that all of us have

906
00:49:34.930 --> 00:49:38.730
in large departments. And so you look into those

907
00:49:38.950 --> 00:49:39.230
and you go,

908
00:49:40.110 --> 00:49:42.720
"Which ones are giving us the greatest gains?" But we wouldn't

909
00:49:43.590 --> 00:49:47.090
make any sort of substantive adjustment to a program we were delivering

910
00:49:47.130 --> 00:49:51.010
without first a discussion with the government or with

911
00:49:51.050 --> 00:49:54.450
ministers. So I think in this whole savings program as we go forward,

912
00:49:54.810 --> 00:49:58.010
the process is probably quite important to understand.

913
00:49:59.270 --> 00:50:02.910
My job is to go back to ministers in the next month or two

914
00:50:03.690 --> 00:50:07.210
with some of the ideas we've got about how we could make more efficiencies.

915
00:50:07.250 --> 00:50:10.800
Those things will be considered by ministers, and then ultimately, probably at

916
00:50:10.830 --> 00:50:13.870
Cabinet for some of those things across the whole public service.

917
00:50:14.250 --> 00:50:17.729
And then, ultimately, that'll lay out a bit of a plan for some of the initiatives

918
00:50:17.770 --> 00:50:21.670
that we'll take on savings. So there's quite a ways to go yet before we

919
00:50:21.810 --> 00:50:25.750
take any direct initiatives. The savings that are already in

920
00:50:25.790 --> 00:50:28.610
train that have come from previous budgets and so on, those are already well

921
00:50:28.710 --> 00:50:29.190
planned for.

922
00:50:29.250 --> 00:50:29.280
Mm.

923
00:50:29.510 --> 00:50:32.830
And as I said, they largely have been able to be taken out through administrative

924
00:50:32.890 --> 00:50:33.210
cost.

925
00:50:33.750 --> 00:50:37.690
And so are you yet to make decisions about which programs may end as a result

926
00:50:37.730 --> 00:50:37.930
of-

927
00:50:38.670 --> 00:50:38.830
Could be-

928
00:50:39.110 --> 00:50:39.750
Finding savings

929
00:50:39.770 --> 00:50:42.870
... could be programs. It tends to be

930
00:50:44.010 --> 00:50:46.790
initiatives rather than big programs that are currently running.

931
00:50:46.850 --> 00:50:50.670
It's not often you see those. But it tends to be initiatives that the department

932
00:50:50.690 --> 00:50:54.090
might be undertaking of working on, or things where the government might consider

933
00:50:54.100 --> 00:50:54.430
actually

934
00:50:55.230 --> 00:50:56.830
that money could be spent on a different priority.

935
00:50:56.870 --> 00:51:00.539
So we'll work together where we think our

936
00:51:00.730 --> 00:51:04.379
budget lines are and what we think we would like to take on in the year where we've

937
00:51:04.390 --> 00:51:05.180
got some discretion.

938
00:51:06.310 --> 00:51:08.460
And that'll be a conversation we have with ministers over the coming months.

939
00:51:08.870 --> 00:51:12.370
There's another part of this, which is around how do you get more for the money

940
00:51:12.430 --> 00:51:16.390
that you have. The $1.33 billion we'll spend

941
00:51:16.450 --> 00:51:19.690
this year, $13.2 million is important.

942
00:51:20.250 --> 00:51:22.870
But perhaps if we can find savings and accommodations,

943
00:51:23.830 --> 00:51:27.590
we continue to do this. So if we take our biosecurity as an example, you've seen us

944
00:51:27.650 --> 00:51:31.550
announce $70 million additional to go into wilding pines because

945
00:51:31.560 --> 00:51:35.530
the case has been made that actually there is a growing problem there.

946
00:51:35.550 --> 00:51:39.340
But before we got to the point of deciding on a quantum of

947
00:51:39.370 --> 00:51:42.930
additional resource for wilding pines, I asked the ministry to go

948
00:51:43.030 --> 00:51:46.470
through what we were doing at the moment and how more effectively and

949
00:51:46.490 --> 00:51:49.569
efficiently we could use that money to get rid of more wilding pines.

950
00:51:49.610 --> 00:51:49.990
Mm.

951
00:51:50.010 --> 00:51:53.250
Because more money in a problem, if the system is not efficient,

952
00:51:53.950 --> 00:51:57.650
creates greater inefficiency, and it takes resource away from somewhere else that

953
00:51:57.710 --> 00:52:01.330
you might use it. If you think about wallabies, whereas in

954
00:52:01.710 --> 00:52:05.290
Canterbury and around Maiot, Ruatāhuna, there is a large

955
00:52:05.390 --> 00:52:09.230
growing population. We've asked the question of how much are we spending, how

956
00:52:09.290 --> 00:52:11.580
many animals are we getting, how can we do that better?

957
00:52:11.990 --> 00:52:14.450
Don't do a big expensive study to tell me that.

958
00:52:14.510 --> 00:52:17.890
Go and find a way to do it better. So there's two things we continue to do.

959
00:52:18.030 --> 00:52:20.630
How can we find savings? Are there projects that actually,

960
00:52:22.230 --> 00:52:26.190
as they come to an end, we don't need to renew them because they have

961
00:52:26.230 --> 00:52:29.450
or haven't achieved what we need? Is there spending that actually could be

962
00:52:29.530 --> 00:52:33.450
reprioritized to achieve much more, or there are savings

963
00:52:33.530 --> 00:52:37.420
equally that we can find through greater efficiency?

964
00:52:37.930 --> 00:52:41.370
So, projects start and finish all the time.

965
00:52:41.430 --> 00:52:45.390
If we take Jobs for Nature, which was under the last government, it was two

966
00:52:45.400 --> 00:52:49.120
and bound. It was four years. They were always estimated to finish at the end of

967
00:52:49.190 --> 00:52:52.850
that. And so that's just the nature of governments making decisions as to where you

968
00:52:52.910 --> 00:52:56.650
spend resource. If you don't make decisions like that, budgets go up, and

969
